    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>It works fine.  Did you read <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/String.html#split-java.lang.String-\" rel=\"nofollow\">the documentation</a>?  The string is converted to a regular expression.</p>\n\n<p><code>.</code> is the special character matching all input characters.</p>\n\n<p>As with any regular expression special character, you escape with a <code>\\</code>.  You need an additional <code>\\</code> for the Java string escape.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 351784,
      "reputation" : 6720,
      "user_id" : 688477,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 80,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b79f00f5e27e39247a38edbdd22f2a22?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "ysrb",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/688477/ysrb"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 15,
    "last_activity_date" : 1426214794,
    "last_edit_date" : 1426214794,
    "creation_date" : 1319844382,
    "answer_id" : 7935872,
    "question_id" : 7935858,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Try:</p>\n\n<pre><code>String words[]=temp.split(\"\\\\.\");\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>The method is:</p>\n\n<pre><code>String[] split(String regex) \n</code></pre>\n\n<p>\".\" is a reserved char in regex</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 28897,
      "reputation" : 387365,
      "user_id" : 77567,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8f74022962edfb2f4bf9e7f497cd14eb?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "rob mayoff",
